Cook,<br><br>
Thanks for your response.<br><br>
Will you let me oversimplify the Scripture about Gideon? He was a Judge. And those who elected, for reasons of their own, to not fight a war which was sanctioned by God were granted &quot;amnesty&quot;. This was a war that God wanted them to fight! Yet they were forgiven. Understood.<br><br>
Was Vietnam a war sanctioned by God? I don't know. What I do know is that if God allowed forgiveness to the people who did not want to fight in a war that He clearly sanctioned, as in the instance of Gideon and the Midianites, why is it impossible for us to forgive those who did not wish to fight in a war that was sanctioned by the likes of JFK, LBJ, and Nixon?  <br><br>
As for ANY who protested the war in Vietnam. I am unable to judge. I don't know what was in Muhammed Ali's heart. Or doc spatz's.<br><br>
I base my opinions on what I saw personally in Vietnam. I give each and all the benefit of the doubt.  I am unable to judge. Does this diminish my service? Or your service? Nope. How would Gideon judge?<br><br>
Regardless of your opinion of the Winter Soldiers, I saw enough during my tour that I am unable to dismiss the testimony in total. It has occurred to me that there was no cross examination. I will grant you that. But, I could stand up against any cross exam, based upon MY first hand knowledge. <br><br>
As for the Quakers aiding and abetting our enemy, I will need sources from you. If you want to send them back channel, that would be good.<br><br>
My status as a former draftee doesn't preclude me from correcting you when you refer to people as &quot;gooks&quot;. Actually, I think enough of you as a person, and a man of the cloth, to want you to know that you do not do yourself or your parishioners justice when you speak in this manner. <br><br>
Peace to you Cook,<br><br>
Tom<br><br>

